name: Trident
description: The stamp depicts the trident - the Small State Emblem of Ukraine. The design is based on the trident from the time of Volodymyr the Great, emphasizing the thousand-year continuity of Ukrainian statehood. This issue became a symbolic harbinger of the year when national symbols gained special significance.

name: Beijing 2022
description: The XXIV Winter Olympic Games will be held from February 4 to 20, 2022 in Beijing. 2,892 athletes will take part in competitions in 7 sports and 24 disciplines, where 109 sets of medals will be awarded. The Games program includes 7 new disciplines. Beijing will become the first city to host both the Summer and Winter Games. The Games motto is "Together for a Shared Future".

name: Medobory Nature Reserve: White Dittany Dictamnus albus
description: Medobory Nature Reserve is a real pearl not only of Ternopil Region but of all Ukraine. It is located in the Podilski Tovtry. The area of the reserve is 9,516.7 ha. The reserve presents a significant diversity of natural values. A special feature of the protected area is the presence of 19 Red Data Book bat species. On the territory of the nature reserve there are many historical and cultural monuments dating to the 10th-13th centuries.

name: Oleksa Novakivskyi. 1872-1935
description: Oleksa Kharlampiiovych Novakivskyi is a Ukrainian painter and teacher. His work is an entire epoch in the development of national Ukrainian painting. His oeuvre includes allegorical canvases on the spiritual and political revival of Ukraine, romantic images of historical figures of the princely and Cossack eras, and portraits of representatives of the spiritual and intellectual elite of the Ukrainian nation. A significant place is devoted to Shevchenko studies. His works are preserved in museums of Ukraine, Poland, Slovakia, Austria, Germany, Canada, and the USA.

name: Russian warship. THAT'S IT!
description: On April 12, 2022, Ukrposhta issued the postage stamps "Russian warship, go ...!", which artistically captured the first days of Russia's military aggression against Ukraine and one of the vivid episodes of Ukrainian resistance to the occupier - the reply of the defenders of Snake Island to the Russian cruiser "Moskva" to the demand to surrender. The very next day after the stamps were issued - April 13 - it became known about a successful operation of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, as a result of which the flagship of Russia's Black Sea Fleet was hit and sank on April 14, 2022. The event added popularity and collectible value to the stamps "Russian warship, go ...!" and led to the release of a new postage stamp "Russian warship ... THAT'S IT!", authored by Borys Hrokh, as with the previous one.

name: Ukrainian Dream
description: The sketch for the postage stamp, envelope, and card was a drawing by eleven-year-old Sofiia Kravchuk from the city of Liuboml, Volyn Region - a prizewinner of the All-Ukrainian drawing and photography competition "What is Ukraine to me?", which took place last year as part of the 30th anniversary of Ukraine's Independence. The competition had 6,134 participants, and organizers received 10,276 works (drawings and photographs). The childhood dream of the young artist Sofiia Kravchuk about a happy future for Ukraine is connected with the winged "Mriia". In Sofiia's drawing, the world's largest and most powerful aircraft, the An-225 "Mriia", decorated with pink flowers, flies to the stars. Unfortunately, during the war on the territory of Ukraine, the legendary Ukrainian aircraft was destroyed. The enemy destroys Ukrainian equipment and ruins settlements, but it cannot destroy WILL and the desire of Ukrainians for FREEDOM, it cannot destroy the UKRAINIAN DREAM. And the plane, we Ukrainians will certainly rebuild and welcome it again in Kyiv at the parade in honor of Ukraine's Independence Day!

name: Good evening, we are from Ukraine!
description: The greeting "Good evening, we are from Ukraine!" became iconic in 2022 after the Russian military invasion of Ukraine. Today these words open broadcasts by journalists, officials, and the military, and they sound in music tracks. It was the phrase "Good evening, we are from Ukraine!" that Ukrainians chose from among five themes presented for voting as the subject for the next wartime postage stamp of Ukraine. In the open competition for the best sketch for the postage stamp "Good evening, we are from Ukraine!", which received 1,500 creative works, the drawing by Anastasiia Bondarets won decisively. Overall, nearly 900,000 respondents took part in the voting. According to the author of the issue, Anastasiia Bondarets, her drawing is about how every Ukrainian does everything depending on them, to the best of their ability, to bring our Victory closer.

name: FREE. UNBROKEN. UNCONQUERED
description: 300 years of dreams of statehood; 105 years of struggle for a free Ukraine; 31 years of building independence; 8 years of defending sovereignty and borders. On February 24, 2022, Russia began a new stage of the eight-year war against Ukraine - a full-scale offensive that has already lasted 6 months. Unexpectedly, the invaders encountered enormous resistance from Ukrainians. Thanks to the resistance of the Armed Forces of Ukraine and self-defense forces, the Russian army suffers huge losses in manpower and equipment every day. And although the enemy launches massive missile and bomb strikes on peaceful Ukrainian cities and villages every day, committing genocide against the Ukrainian people, the nation remains unconquered. In the struggle for freedom, Ukrainians show incredible heroism, patriotism, resilience, and love for their homeland, each in their place, contributing their crucial input to Victory. With the postal issue "FREE. UNBROKEN. UNCONQUERED" we honor Ukrainians who have become true heroes for the whole world!

name: Patron the Dog: Patron helps farmers
description: The postal issue is dedicated to Patron the dog, a favorite of adults and children, a talisman of Ukrainian rescuers, and a welcome guest at public events. Since the beginning of the war, the Jack Russell terrier named Patron has served in a team of explosives experts of the State Emergency Service of Ukraine. Two years ago, the head of the pyrotechnic group of the Main Directorate of the SES of Ukraine in the Chernihiv Region gave his son a puppy. The four-legged one was prepared for shows, but because of the war he had to become a sapper. In addition to service, Patron attends press conferences, meetings with foreign leaders, and visits children in hospitals. Patron was awarded the medal "For Devoted Service". The "Patron the Dog" stamps are the first charity postage stamps of Ukraine issued with an additional denomination of 8 UAH. Charitable contributions collected by Ukrposhta in this way were used to purchase a mechanized demining machine and to provide assistance to animal shelters.

name: Skovoroda: Garden of Divine Songs (part 1)
description: Hryhorii Skovoroda is a powerful thinker, an interesting writer, an extraordinary personality any European culture would be proud of. He was born in the urban-type settlement of Chornukhy (Poltava Region). He studied at the Kyiv-Mohyla Academy. He preferred personal spiritual freedom - led an ascetic lifestyle and spent much time traveling. Among the creative legacy of Hryhorii Skovoroda are philosophical works and collections of songs and fables ("Garden of Divine Songs", "Kharkiv Fables"). Skovoroda's sayings, mainly about ethics, became very popular: "Love arises from love...", "Do what you were born to do...", "...care is the movement of the soul, and life is movement", and so on. Many collections of aphorisms were compiled from them. His authorial phrase - "The world tried to catch me, but did not" - has become especially relevant today, since the philosopher was not "caught" by Russian aggressors either. On May 6, 2022, Russian troops hit the building of the H.S. Skovoroda National Literary and Memorial Museum in the village of Skovorodynivka (Kharkiv Region) with a missile, where the thinker lived and worked in his later years. Although the building was severely damaged and burned inside, authentic items of the museum collection related to Skovoroda's life and work were preserved. The philosopher's statue also survived. The stamp block consists of two stamps. One depicts Skovoroda's drawing - a fountain symbolizing the philosopher's concept of "unequal equality". The other stamp in the block depicts Hryhorii Skovoroda in full height.

name: Cultural Eras of Ukraine: Sarmatians
description: The Sarmatians were Iranian-speaking nomadic tribes that in the Early Iron Age lived in the steppes from the Ural region to the Danube. From the 2nd century BC to the 4th century AD, the Ukrainian steppes were inhabited by the Sarmatian tribes of the Roxolani, Iazyges, Aorsi, and Alans.

name: Glory to the Armed Forces of Ukraine: "Air Assault Forces of the Armed Forces of Ukraine"
description: The postal issue is dedicated to the defenders of Ukraine who defend the sacred Ukrainian land and to those who gave their lives protecting the sovereignty and territorial integrity of our state. The Armed Forces of Ukraine are one of the best armies in the world, demonstrating professionalism, courage, high combat capability, and ingenuity in confronting a powerful enemy. The stamp sheet "Glory to the Armed Forces of Ukraine!" contains postage stamps depicting servicemen of the Ground Forces, Air Forces, Navy, Air Assault Forces, Special Operations Forces, and Territorial Defense Forces of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, who give a worthy rebuff to the aggressor and defend the State on land, in the air, and at sea.

name: Europa. Stories and Myths: Svarog
description: Ukrainian postal issue under the Europa program on the theme "Stories and Myths" is dedicated to the ancient Slavic gods Svarog and Lada. Svarog is the god of fire and smithcraft. It is believed that Svarog created the Universe, Earth, all animals on it, and people, and established marriage laws. The earliest written source where Svarog is mentioned is "The Tale of Bygone Years". A sign in the shape of a cross - the Svarha - is associated with Svarog and is a symbol of holiness and spiritual strength. Lada is the goddess of motherhood, spring, love, and marriage. According to legends, she was the wife of the god Svarog and the mother of Lelia and Polel. In Slavic mythology, Lada appears as a beautiful woman adorned with roses and ears of grain. Her name is mentioned in ancient Ukrainian spring songs. The author of the issue, Ukrainian artist Mykola Kochubei, used signs in the sketches which, intertwining in the plot, turn symbols into images. Thus, in the festive women's round dance and in the swift run of horses the Svarha sign is encoded, and in the double DNA spiral - the endless movement and process of evolution.

name: Weapons of Victory: MLRS "Vilkha"
description: From the first days of the full-scale war, the Armed Forces of Ukraine have used weapons of both domestic and foreign production on the battlefield, which in the hands of Ukrainian soldiers bring Ukraine closer to Victory every day. "Vilkha" is a multiple launch rocket system designed to hit armored, lightly armored, and unarmored vehicles at long ranges (Ukraine). "Neptune" is a coastal anti-ship missile system with anti-ship cruise missiles designed to defeat warships (Ukraine). On 13.04.2022, the Russian cruiser "Moskva" was destroyed by Neptune missiles of the Armed Forces of Ukraine. "Stugna-P" is a man-portable anti-tank guided missile system designed to engage moving and stationary armored targets (Ukraine). "Bayraktar TB2" is an unmanned aerial vehicle with long endurance (Turkey). FGM-148 "Javelin" is a man-portable anti-tank guided missile system designed to defeat armored vehicles, ground fortifications, and some aerial targets (USA).
